{"id":"1901.04093","submitter":"Krista Soderlund","authors":"Krista Soderlund","title":"Ocean dynamics of outer solar system satellites","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1029/2018GL081880","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.geo-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Ocean worlds are prevalent in the solar system. Focusing on Enceladus, Titan,\nEuropa, and Ganymede, I use rotating convection theory and numerical\nsimulations to predict ocean currents and the potential for ice-ocean coupling.\nWhen the influence of rotation is relatively strong, the oceans have multiple\nzonal jets, axial convective motions, and most efficient heat transfer at high\nlatitudes. This regime is most relevant to Enceladus and possibly to Titan, and\nmay help explain their long-wavelength topography. For a more moderate\nrotational influence, fewer zonal jets form, Hadley-like circulation cells\ndevelop, and heat flux peaks near the equator. This regime is predicted for\nEuropa, where it may help drive geologic activity via thermocompositional\ndiapirism in the ice shell, and is possible for Titan. Weak rotational\ninfluence allows concentric zonal flows and overturning cells with no preferred\norientation. Predictions for Ganymede's ocean span multiple regimes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 14 Jan 2019 00:04:02 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 30 May 2019 19:55:58 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 22 Jul 2019 20:41:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-07-24"}
